-- Bank of China, Citic Securities, Angang, Hunan Valin: China Equity Preview
-- Bloomberg News
-- 2010-07-05T00:19:56Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-04/bank-of-china-angang-steel-hunan-valin-shenzhen-china-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
 unusual  price changes in China trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and share prices are as of the close on July 2.  
 The  Shanghai Composite Index , which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, gained 9.11, or 0.4 percent, to
2,382.90. The  CSI 300 Index  rose 0.3 percent to 2,534.10.  
 Shipping companies: The Baltic Dry Index, a measure of
commodity-shipping costs, fell 3 percent to 2,280 points in
London on July 2, a 26th consecutive decline and the longest
losing streak since August 2005.  
 China Cosco Holdings Co.  (601919 CH), the nation’s biggest
shipping company by market value, slid 0.5 percent to 8.46 yuan.
 China Shipping Container Lines Co.  (601866 CH), the second
largest, dropped 0.9 percent to 3.28 yuan.  
 Brokerages: China asked the nation’s listed securities
companies to strengthen information management for better public
monitoring and to prevent conflicts of interest, according to a
statement posted on the government’s website July 3.  
 Citic Securities Co.  (600030 CH), the nation’s largest
brokerage by market value, rose 1.6 percent to 11.59 yuan.
 Haitong Securities Co.  (600837 CH), the second biggest brokerage,
added 1 percent to 9.15 yuan.  
 Angang Steel Co.  (000898 CH): The steelmaker’s parent,
Anshan Iron & Steel Group, ran into opposition for its proposal
to invest in a Mississippi factory from U.S. lawmakers and a
representative of competitors such as Nucor Corp.  
 A group of 50 lawmakers from districts with steel plants
wrote Treasury Secretary Timothy F. Geithner July 2 that an
investment by the company, which they said is controlled by a
Chinese government entity, poses a national security risk.
Angang’s shares rose 1.4 percent at 7.25 yuan.  
 Bank of China Ltd.  (601988 CH)): Asia’s third-largest
lender by market value plans to raise as much as 60 billion yuan
($8.9 billion) in a rights offer to replenish capital. The
lender said July 2 it will sell shares in Shanghai and Hong Kong.
The stock rose 0.3 percent to 3.4 yuan.  
 China Petroleum & Chemical Corp.  (600028 CH): The nation’s
largest oil refiner will cut daily oil processing volume at its
Hainan plant by 11 percent this month from June as profit
shrinks, a refinery official said July 2. Shares rose 0.3
percent to 7.83 yuan.  
 China Shenhua Energy Co.  (601088 CH): The company said July
2 its thermal power plant in Shaanxi province began generating
electricity. Shares dropped 0.2 percent to 21.69 yuan.  
 Chongqing Brewery Co.  (600132 CH): Carlsberg A/S’s purchase
of a further stake in Chongqing Brewery is not a “problem,”
the Danish company said July 2, responding to reports that the
acquisition may be halted by Chinese authorities. Chongqing
Brewery’s shares fell 6.2 percent to 32.85 yuan.  
 Hunan Valin Steel Co.  (000932 CH): ArcelorMittal won
Chinese government approval for an auto sheet production venture
with Valin Steel’s parent, Hunan Valin Iron & Steel Group,
Reuters reported July 2, citing an unidentified spokeswoman with
the steelmaker. Shares of the Shenzhen-listed steelmaker rose
2.4 percent to 3.87 yuan.  
 Shenzhen Development Bank Co.  (000001 CH): The lender
raised 6.93 billion yuan from its private share placement to
Ping An Insurance (Group) Co. The stock fell 5.3 percent to
17.51 yuan on June 29, when its shares last traded.  
 Zhongjin Gold Co.  (600489 CH): The gold producer will pay a
cash dividend of 0.15 yuan a share and 0.8 bonus share for each
share held, according to a statement to the stock exchange. The
shares 4.9 percent to 46.64 yuan.  
 -- Zhang Shidong ,  Li Yanping ,  Chua Kong Ho . Editor:  Ben Richardson , Richard Frost  
